Resources on how to get out of these vulnerable conditions. For ex: away from a violent household, how to get sober etc. Planning before discharge/release, especially in the case of people leaving from institutions like jails and foster homes. Preparing them for what to expect in the world and how they can get a job and lead a stable life. What are the resources available to them?

(when leaving foster home/jail): I need help finding a job when I get out; I need help getting access to resources; I need help building a good credit score; I need help finding an affordable place to live; I need help staying out of the 'bad' circles; I need help building a new life for myself - achieving goals and ambitions; I need help in realizing my potential and identifying my passions and ambitions. (in bad living conditions) : I need to know how to get myself out of this situation, who to go to for help and how I can build a normal life again on my own
(when losing job/income) : I need help maintaining my current expenses (rent, groceries etc.); I need help finding a new job and managing my expenses I need help paying my utilities

(getting evicted) : I need help paying the rent; I need to buy more time from my landlord/landlady so I can look for a job; I need help finding a jobI need to know where else I can stay for cheaper (given my current loss of income)

I need a safe space to live (after being kicked out of my house) for an affordable price I need help finding alternative jobs for additional income I need help budgeting my finances to last longer ( where can I cut costs?)

I need extra food, utilities, help managing my kids (babysitting) while i work I need help paying my phone bill/utility bill, hotel/motel bill etc. I need help finding a cost-effective place to stay for longer I need help finding a job for financial assistance

I need a place to stay for free/very low rent that is safe for my family and I I need a flexible 'landlord' situation - I'm unsure how long it'll take to get back to my original condition; need a place that is a little flexible to my current condition and needsI need help splitting the rent with my family/friends or coming up with an agreeable pay-back/exchange of resources system
I need help finding and keeping a job I need help managing my finances I need help quitting my bad habits (drugs, alcohol etc.)
I need help managing my stress and sharing the work load in the shared household. I need help communicating with the relative/friend to make sure I do not ruin that relationship

I need help finding a safe, free place to spend the night I need help finding available shelters/resources where I can find a more semi-permanent solution I need help finding food and access to a shower I need help staying out of the cold

(if I have a job): I need to find out how to keep my job despite being homeless so I do not fall back into financial strain. ( if I have kids): I need help raising my kids, making sure they are safe and their lifestyle isn't affected
I need help knowing how to best get access to the available resources. I need help filling out my application correctly so I can qualify for help fast
I need help knowing exactly how and who to ask for help.
I need a cell phone/address where I can receive follow up calls from these shelters. I need interim housing and food/hygiene resources
I need help building a "plan B", in case i do not qualify/do not make it off the waiting list.
I need a stable housing situation, where I feel safe and can count on having that roof over my head on a regular basis
I need to know how to prepare my documentation to qualify for long-term housing
I need help saving up enough $ to move out of the shelter system (financial planning)
I need help staying clean and maintaining my job
I need help not re-entering the system again I need help ensuring my children do not follow the same pattern and enter the shelter system
I need help quitting my bad habits and staying clean I need basic amenities like food, water etc. I need access to mental and physical health care
Because they are staying in these conditions for a while, kind of used to it. This is their normal. Don't think it can get any worse than this.

How other people deal with these sudden emergencies. Social support - how to connect with others in similar situations. Resources that connect them to new jobs, employment opportunities, housing assistance.
Sad, shock, overwhelmed. Trying to come to terms with what happened, but believe that 'it's not that bad' and it's a temporary phase and can still get through it. Controllable damage.

text.tspan: out of options and need to find

svg.text: Damage control. Budgeting/planning to make their money and available resources last for as long as they can muster.
"This is temporary. I will need it till I get back on my feet" Usually consider it a short-term situation, which will be quickly remedied.
Ran out of their own resources, so immediate need to reach out for help to their closest friends/relatives network.
No more a temporary situation. This is really bad and I need some help (from an external source)

Motivated to look for help and other resources but feeling helpless/overwhelmed at inability to remedy situation. If person has good relationship with who they are doubling up with, it's a sense of relief that they have someone that they can count on.

text.tspan: In search of help from formal

svg.text: This phase is marked by a sense of hopefulness (at receiving help) and hopelessness (the wait-time, the temporary nature of it all can cause a lot of anxiety and street about not knowing where you will be tomorrow, whether you will qualify, where you can stay etc.)
Anxiety at not knowing what will happen and where the person will stay for the night/upcoming nights.

text.tspan: changing their life and trying to
Hopeful that this can be their

svg.text: Hopeful that they can exit the system. Determined never to enter it again.

Disappointment. Not wanting to return to this system again, having gone through it once/twice already. Maybe a sense of resentment - even after going through a tough struggle and doing so well, they may end up back in the same system.
Sad, but hopeful that they will get out of this soon.

How to prevent it from getting to the point of an eviction. What are some of the resources they can take advantage of instead of going to stay in a hotel/motel? Can organizations help give financial assistance/budgeting to help them get back on their feet?

Resources that can help them stretch and plan their budgets and what they can do in the meantime to improve their circumstances.There are several resources available by both, govt and non - govt organizations that they can take advantage of for transportation, food, medical assistance etc. However, this info is not known by all and isn't easily available. Maybe making info available to them when they need it most, in a way that's easy to consume could be helpful.

Connections to food banks in the neighborhood, discount markets, restaurants with cheap food options. Teaching them about budgeting and how best to reduce their credit card debt and other economical hacks.
Assistance in filling out and applying to jobs. Connections and awareness of available positions in the vicinity and helping them procure the jobs(recommendation letters etc.)

Assistance in planning out how they can use this time "doubled up" to help them get back on their feet. Preventing them from losing this resource (For ex: diversion). Can they have some spreadsheets / materials that help them plan how much to budget based on size of household and from other experiences state what to and what not to do to avoid losing this housing.

Information/resources that connect them to other available resources that provide temporary shelter, showers, food etc. Connect them directly to the shelter system and get their paperwork ready so that they aren't completely homeless for a brief period of time.
Making the process easy and streamlined. Instead of having them fill out paperwork multiple times, can they use one data point to connect them to a myriad of resources?

Many of the people calling in do not have cell phones/ a permanent address they can be contacted at. Can they be provided with an easy way to get in touch with these shelters on the status of their application? Alternatively, can there be interim help provided to them?
Many of these people may need permanent housing in the future. So provide helpful resources to aid them in qualifying. For ex: rehab resources to wean off from drug/alcohol use.

svg.text: Before they exit one shelter system, provide them with resources that will help them be self-sufficient. It's not just about housing, but about mental/physical health, about food, job security etc. Can it also be about providing these services and learnings?

text.tspan: follows up and checks up on

svg.text: Build a support community - connect them to others who may be in challenging situations so they help each other avoid falling into patterns (of using substances, gambling etc.)
Help them set up a savings account (to plan for any sudden emergencies etc.), and practice healthy spending and budgeting to manage their expenses.

Instead of having to go through the entire system again, connecting with someone who knows their case (maybe their previous case manager) and working with them to figure out the easiest/more effective way to get out of their current situation.
